Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows a small area that is slightly concave, perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of 0.2 cm. The front side is flat and shows part of a seal with a circumferential line. Visible is a seated figure at the top, probably a lion or a dog, with a small sign above the back, maybe a t, underneath a flat and elongated sign, maybe a crocodile. The rest is broken off.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
